Problem 1

Creating a dataframe

The chunk below creates a dataframe containing a sample of size 10 from a random uniform[0,5] distributed variable, a logical vector indicating whether elements of the sample are greater than 2, a (length-10) character vector, and a (length-10) factor vector.

set.seed(1)

unif_samp = runif(n = 10, min = 0, max = 5)
vec_logical = unif_samp > 2
vec_char = c("This", "is", "my", "first", "homework", 
               "using", "R", "for", "data", "science")
vec_factor = factor(c("less", "less", "greater", "greater", 
                        "less", "greater", "greater", "greater", 
                        "greater", "less"))

prob1_df = tibble(unif_samp, vec_logical, vec_char, vec_factor)

Taking the mean of each variable

We will try to take the mean of each variable in the dataframe and see which variables return a mean value and which variables will not.

  • Only numeric or logical variables will return a mean.
    • The mean for unif_samp is 2.7575694.
    • The mean for vec_logical is 0.6.
  • Character and factor variables will not return a mean.
    • The mean for vec_char is NA.
    • The mean for vec_factor is NA.

Explicitly converting variables

Converting into a numeric variable

The chunk below will explicitly convert logical, character, and factor variables into a numeric variable.

as.numeric(vec_logical)
as.numeric(vec_char)
as.numeric(vec_factor)

The logical and factor variables were able to be converted into a numeric variable, but R was unable to turn a character variable into a numeric one (NAs introduced by coercion).

Converting a character variable

The chunk below will convert the character variable from character to factor to numeric

as.factor(vec_char)
as.numeric(vec_char)

R was able to convert the character variable to a factor variable and created 10 levels. R was unable to convert the character variable to a numeric variable (NAs introduced by coercion).

Converting a factor variable

The chunk below will convert the factor variable from factor to character to numeric

as.character(vec_factor)
as.numeric(vec_factor)

R was able to convert the factor variable to both a character and numeric variable. Now, there are 10 characters as opposed to 2 levels. There are only 2 numbers used - 1 to signify greater and 2 to signify less.

Problem 2

Creating a dataframe for variables x and y

The chunk below creates a dataframe comprised of x (a random sample of size 1000 from a standard Normal distribution), y (a random sample of size 1000 from a standard Normal distribution), a logical vector indicating whether the x + y > 0, a numeric vector created by coercing the above logical vector, and a factor vector created by coercing the above logical vector.

set.seed(1)

x = rnorm(1000)
y = rnorm(1000)
xy_logical = x + y > 0
num_coerc = as.numeric(xy_logical)
fac_coerc = as.factor(xy_logical)

prob2_df = tibble(x, y, xy_logical, num_coerc, fac_coerc)

The mean for x is -0.0116481 and the median for x is -0.0353242.

Scatterplot of x and y

The chunk below will create a scatterplot of y vs x.

ggplot(prob2_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = xy_logical)) + geom_point()

ggplot(prob2_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = num_coerc)) + geom_point()

ggplot(prob2_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = fac_coerc)) + geom_point()
